To create a short, shareable string from a long one, you can use various methods such as Base64 encoding, URL encoding, or hash functions. Here's an example using Base64 encoding in JavaScript:

```javascript
function encodeBase64(str) {
  return btoa(String.fromCharCode.apply(null, new Uint8Array(new TextEncoder('ascii').encode(str)));
}

function btoa(arr) {
  return arr.map(function(byte) {
    return String.fromCharCode(byte);
  }).join('');
}

// Usage
const longString = "your_long_string_here";
const shortString = encodeBase64(longString);
console.log(shortString);
```

To decode the short string, you can use the following function:

```javascript
function atob(str) {
  return String.fromCharCode.apply(null, new Uint8Array(atob.buffer = atob(str)));
}
atob.buffer = null;

// Usage
const shortString = "your_encoded_string_here";
const decodedString = atob(shortString);
console.log(decodedString);
```

Keep in mind that Base64 encoding will increase the length of your string by approximately 33%. If you need a shorter string, you might want to consider using a URL-safe Base64 encoding or a hash function like SHA-256.

For URL-safe Base64 encoding, you can modify the `encodeBase64` function like this:

```javascript
function encodeBase64UrlSafe(str) {
  const encoded = encodeBase64(str);
  return encoded.replace(/\+/g, '-').replace(/\//g, '_');
}
```

And for decoding, you can use:

```javascript
function decodeBase64UrlSafe(str) {
  str = str.replace(/-/g, '+').replace(/_/g, '/');
  return atob(str);
}
